# Logitech TrueForce wheels: hidraw + wheel_* sysfs access
#
# Grants the currently-logged-in desktop user access, with no group
# membership required (systemd-logind uaccess for the hidraw device node;
# world-writable mode on the wheel_* sysfs knobs, which uaccess does not
# cover). This is why the settings apps work with no terminal setup.
#   - /dev/hidraw*  for libtrueforce / userspace tooling and the
#     Logitech SDK DLLs' TrueForce stream under Proton
#   - /sys/class/hidraw/hidrawN/device/wheel_*  for Oversteer, the
#     in-tree sysfs knobs, and user scripts
#
# Without this rule the sysfs knobs are mode 0664 root:root and every
# wheel_* write needs sudo. Mode 0666 lets any local user change wheel
# settings; on a single-user desktop (the norm for a personal wheel) this
# is the friction-free default, matching other Linux wheel udev rules.
#
# Supported USB product IDs (VID 046D), grouped by capability - all get
# the same hidraw access:
#
#   Direct-drive TrueForce wheels (this driver's primary targets):
#     C276  RS50 Direct Drive - NATIVE mode (full sysfs surface)
#     C272  G PRO Racing Wheel (Xbox/PC) - ALSO the RS50 in G PRO
#           COMPATIBILITY mode (the RS50 can present this PID; the
#           driver tells the two apart by USB product string). The SDK
#           also accepts the RS50's native C276, so compat mode is not
#           required for TrueForce.
#     C268  G PRO Racing Wheel (PlayStation/PC)
#
#   Gear-driven, but same TrueForce stream protocol - access is purely
#   so the SDK DLLs can reach the wheel under Proton:
#     C266  G923 (PlayStation/PC)
#     C26D  G923 (Xbox/PC, alt PID)
#     C26E  G923 (Xbox/PC)
#
#   No TrueForce - kept only for its range knob:
#     C262  G920 Racing Wheel

ACTION!="add|change", GOTO="trueforce_end"
SUBSYSTEM!="hidraw", GOTO="trueforce_end"

# One alternation instead of a GOTO per PID: adding a wheel is a
# five-character diff that cannot forget the GOTO.
ATTRS{idVendor}=="046d", ATTRS{idProduct}=="c262|c266|c26d|c26e|c268|c272|c276", GOTO="trueforce_apply"
GOTO="trueforce_end"

LABEL="trueforce_apply"

# /dev/hidraw* for libtrueforce and direct userspace tooling.
TAG+="uaccess", MODE="0660"

# wheel_* sysfs attributes (only exist on the HID++ interface's hidraw
# node; the RUN invocation is a no-op on interfaces that lack them).
# Note: "$$f" not "$f" - udev treats a lone "$" as a substitution
# marker, so a literal shell "$f" must be written "$$f" (passes
# udevadm verify; on lenient udev versions "$f" happened to survive
# as a literal, but that is non-portable).
RUN+="/bin/sh -c 'for f in /sys/class/hidraw/%k/device/wheel_* /sys/class/hidraw/%k/device/range /sys/class/hidraw/%k/device/gain /sys/class/hidraw/%k/device/autocenter /sys/class/hidraw/%k/device/combine_pedals /sys/class/hidraw/%k/device/damper_level /sys/class/hidraw/%k/device/spring_level /sys/class/hidraw/%k/device/friction_level; do [ -e \"$$f\" ] || continue; chmod 0666 \"$$f\"; done'"

LABEL="trueforce_end"
